README

  Please, at least SKIM this document before asking questions. In fact,
  READ IT if you've never successfully set up an Eggdrop bot before.

FORK NOTICE

  This is a personal fork of Eggdrop maintained by devinkbrown. It is
  not an official Eggdrop release. The upstream project lives at:

      https://github.com/eggheads/eggdrop

  Why this fork exists:

    Upstream Eggdrop has excellent IRC bot functionality but carries
    decades of build-system and portability debt. This fork was created
    to modernise those areas:

      1. The autoconf/make build system is replaced with Meson + Ninja,
         which is faster, easier to maintain, and works out of the box
         on Linux, macOS, Windows (MinGW and MSVC), and Cygwin.

      2. Native Windows support (without Cygwin) has never existed in
         upstream. This fork adds it — including a proper IOCP I/O
         backend — so Eggdrop can run as a first-class Windows process.

  Why libop is used here:

         Eggdrop's existing I/O loop (net.c) was written for POSIX and
         had no path for Windows async I/O whatsoever. Writing IOCP from
         scratch inside a foreign codebase is error-prone: getting the
         overlapped structure layout right, handling stale completions
         after a socket is closed, draining the completion port safely,
         and avoiding double-frees are all subtle failure modes.

         libop is the I/O layer of the ophion project
         (https://github.com/devinkbrown/ophion), written by the same
         author. It had already solved all of those problems in
         production-tested C:

           - Zero-byte overlapped WSARecv/WSASend arms readiness
             notifications without touching the data buffer, matching
             exactly how epoll/kqueue signal readability.
           - The OVERLAPPED struct is the first member of every pending
             operation, so GetQueuedCompletionStatus results cast back
             to the pending struct without undefined behaviour.
           - Stale completions (arriving after the socket is closed) are
             detected by recording the socket fd and slot index at arm
             time and checking them on arrival.
           - Read/write arms are tracked per-slot so the port is never
             double-armed.

         Adapting libop's design meant the Windows backend could be
         dropped into Eggdrop in a single coherent pass and reviewed as
         a unit, rather than being bolted on piece by piece over time.

      3. All five major platforms (Linux/io_uring, Linux/epoll,
         macOS+BSD/kqueue, Windows/IOCP, fallback/select) now have a
         native, scalable I/O backend.

    If upstream picks up these changes this fork may be retired or
    rebased on top of upstream. Until then it tracks upstream bug fixes
    and pulls them in as they land.

  Notable differences from upstream:

    - TOML configuration format: eggdrop.toml replaces the Tcl-script
      config. Legacy .conf files still work unchanged.
        · Run 'eggdrop --setup' for a five-step interactive wizard:
          network-type menu, SSL/TLS + SASL, multiple channels, smart
          nick-derived defaults, pre-write summary and confirmation.
          Generated config covers every section and setting.
        · Full setting parity with eggdrop.conf: all 128+ Tcl variables
          are documented in eggdrop.toml with correct key names.
        · Per-channel settings via [[chanset]] blocks: all 26 flags and
          all valued options including chanmode, flood thresholds, etc.
        · Auto-create userfile on first run when owner = "Nick" is set
          in the config — no -m flag needed for new TOML installs.
        · Inline Tcl via [tcl] commands = [...] for one-liners or
          [tcl] code = """...""" for multi-line proc/bind blocks.
        · No 'chmod u+x' required.
    - IRCX/Ophion protocol support: set net_type = "Ophion" to enable
      full IRCX mode negotiation, +q (channel owner) mode handling, and
      channel CREATE/PROP/ACCESS commands.  New Tcl API: ircxprop,
      ircxaccess, ircxcreate, ircxautoowner.  OWNERKEY credentials
      persist to the channel file across restarts.
    - io_uring SQPOLL: fixed three bugs that prevented IRC registration
      on kernels using SQPOLL mode (SQPOLL tail flush, buffered recv
      data overwrite, idle-return before dispatch).
    - Build system replaced: autoconf/make → Meson + Ninja
    - Native Windows (MinGW / MSVC) support via IOCP event backend
    - Cygwin legacy hacks removed; Cygwin compiles on the POSIX path
    - I/O backends, auto-selected in priority order:

        Platform                  Backend
        ------------------------  ----------
        Linux >= 5.1 + liburing   io_uring
        Linux                     epoll
        macOS / FreeBSD / OpenBSD / NetBSD   kqueue  (upstream v1.10.1)
        Windows native            IOCP
        Cygwin / fallback         select()

    - BSD and macOS are fully covered by the kqueue backend inherited
      from upstream v1.10.1; no select() fallback is used there
    - Build warning cleanup: all -Wsizeof-pointer-memaccess and
      -Wformat-truncation warnings eliminated. snprintf calls now use
      the correct buffer length instead of sizeof(char *). The nstrdup
      macro redefinition and the Python 3.14 _POSIX_C_SOURCE conflict
      are also resolved. The tree builds clean with GCC 15.
    - Build optimizations: LTO enabled by default; -fno-strict-aliasing
      applied globally (eggdrop uses void*/char* casts); -Wl,--as-needed
      on ELF platforms; module .so files built with -fvisibility=hidden
      so only entry points are exported. Optional -march=native tuning
      via -Dnative-opt=false (on by default; -mcpu=native on
      ARM/AArch64/PowerPC, -march=native everywhere else).
    - Various bug fixes and patches under review for upstream inclusion

  Issues and changes specific to this fork should be reported at the
  fork repository. General Eggdrop questions can still be directed to
  the upstream channels listed in the OBTAINING HELP section below.

NOTICE

  Make SURE that you select your +n (owner) users wisely. They have 100%
  access to your bot and account. ONLY GIVE THIS POWER TO SOMEONE YOU
  TRUST COMPLETELY!

WHAT IS EGGDROP?

  Eggdrop is the world's most popular Internet Relay Chat (IRC) bot; it
  is freely distributable under the GNU General Public License (GPL).
  Eggdrop is a feature-rich program designed to be easily used and
  expanded upon by both novice and advanced IRC users on a variety of
  hardware and software platforms.

  An IRC bot is a program that sits on an IRC channel and performs
  automated tasks while looking just like a normal user on the channel.
  Some of these functions include protecting the channel from abuse,
  allowing privileged users to gain op or voice status, logging channel
  events, providing information, hosting games, etc.

  One of the features that makes Eggdrop stand out from other bots is
  module and Tcl and Python scripting support. With scripts and modules
  you can make the bot perform almost any task you want. They can do
  anything: from preventing floods to greeting users and banning
  advertisers from channels.

  You can also link multiple Eggdrop bots together to form a botnet.
  This can allow bots to op each other securely, control floods
  efficiently and even link channels across multiple IRC networks. It
  also allows the Eggdrops share user lists, ban/exempt/invite lists,
  and ignore lists with other bots if userfile sharing is enabled. This
  allows users to have the same access on every bot on your botnet. It
  also allows the bots to distribute tasks such as opping and banning
  users. See doc/BOTNET for information on setting up a botnet.

  Eggdrop is always being improved and adjusted because there are bugs
  to be fixed and features to be added (if the users demand them and
  they make actually sense). In fact, it existed for several years as
  v0.7 - v0.9 before finally going 1.0. This version of Eggdrop is part
  of the 1.10 tree. A valiant effort has been made to chase down and
  destroy bugs.

  This README file contains information about how to get Eggdrop,
  command line options for Eggdrop, what you may need to do when
  upgrading from older versions, a list of frequently asked questions,
  how to set up a crontab, some boring legal stuff, some basics about
  git usage and some channels where you might get help with Eggdrop.

HOW TO GET EGGDROP

There are two official methods to download Eggdrop source code.
Alternately, Eggdrop also comes as a docker image.

FTP

  The latest Eggdrop stable source code is always located at
  https://geteggdrop.com. You can also download the current stable,
  previous stable, and development snapshot at
  https://ftp.eggheads.org/pub/eggdrop/source

Git Development Snapshot

  Eggdrop developers use git to manage the Eggdrop codebase for
  development. If you are interested in trying out the VERY LATEST
  updates to Eggdrop, you can use git to obtain most recent code from
  the Eggheads repository. BE WARNED, the development branch of Eggdrop
  is not to be considered stable and may (haha) contain significant bugs
  still being worked on.

  To obtain Eggdrop via the git repository (hosted by GitHub), you can
  either clone the repository via git or download a development
  snapshot.

  To clone this fork, simply type:

      git clone https://github.com/devinkbrown/eggdrop.git

  To clone the upstream Eggdrop repository instead:

      git clone https://github.com/eggheads/eggdrop.git

  Otherwise, you can download the upstream development snapshot as a tar
  archive from:

    https://github.com/eggheads/eggdrop/archive/develop.tar.gz

Docker

  You can pull the official Eggdrop Docker image via:

      docker pull eggdrop:latest

  Additional Eggdrop Docker documentation can be found at
  https://hub.docker.com/_/eggdrop

SYSTEM PRE-REQUISITES

  This fork builds with Meson + Ninja. You will need both installed in
  addition to the library dependencies below.

  Tcl must be installed on your system. Many systems have Tcl installed
  by default (check by running "tclsh"; a '%' prompt means it is
  present). Eggdrop also requires the Tcl development header files,
  usually packaged as 'tcl-dev' or 'tcl-devel'. Source is available at
  https://www.tcl.tk/software/tcltk/download.html.

  Tcl is optional in this fork.  To build without Tcl and use Python
  as the sole scripting engine:

      meson setup builddir/ -Dtcl=disabled
      ninja -C builddir/

  With Tcl disabled, python.mod is automatically used for all scripts
  listed in the [scripts] TOML section.  See PYTHON SCRIPTING below.

  OpenSSL (and its development headers) is required to enable SSL/TLS
  protection of network data. Headers are usually packaged as
  'libssl-dev'. TLS can be disabled at configure time:

      meson setup build/ -Dtls=disabled

  but you will not be able to connect to TLS-protected IRC servers or
  use secure botnet links.

  On native Windows (MinGW / MSVC), Winsock2 and MsWSock are required
  for the IOCP backend; both ship with the Windows SDK and are linked
  automatically by the build system.

MINIMUM REQUIREMENTS

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Functionality                   Package             Minimum Version
  ------------------------------- ------------------- -------------------
  Build system (required)         Meson               0.57.0
  Build system (required)         Ninja               Any recent

  Tcl interpreter (optional)      Tcl Dev Library     8.6.0

  Secure communication            OpenSSL             1.0.0

  Python module                   Python              3.8.0

  Compression module              zlib                Any

  I/O: IOCP (Windows native)      Windows SDK         Windows 7+
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Note: Tcl is now optional.  Python 3.8+ is sufficient to run scripts
  when Tcl is not installed.  At least one of Tcl or Python must be
  present in the build for scripting support.

CONFIGURATION

  This fork uses TOML as the primary configuration format. TOML is a
  modern, human-readable format that requires no knowledge of Tcl.

  QUICK METHOD — interactive wizard (recommended for new installs):

      eggdrop --setup mybot.toml

    Five-step guided flow:
      1. Bot identity — nick, altnick/realname/username auto-derived
      2. IRC server   — network-type menu, hostname, SSL/TLS, port,
                        server password, optional SASL authentication
      3. Channels     — up to 8 channels, first required
      4. Files        — user/chan/log, defaults from nick
      5. Modules      — notes, seen, transfer, filesys

    Prints a summary and asks for confirmation before writing.
    No 'chmod u+x' required.

  MANUAL METHOD — copy and edit the sample file:

      cp eggdrop-basic.toml mybot.toml
      $EDITOR mybot.toml          # at minimum set nick, servers, owner

  CONFIG FORMAT:

      [bot]
      nick    = "MyBot"
      altnick = "MyBot?"
      owner   = "MyNick"

      [servers]
      list = ["irc.libera.chat:+6697"]

      [channels]
      list = ["#mychannel", "#egghelp"]

      [modules]
      load = ["pbkdf2", "blowfish", "channels", "server", "ctcp", "irc",
              "notes", "console", "uptime"]

      [scripts]
      load = ["scripts/alltools.tcl"]

      # One-liner Tcl commands run after settings are applied:
      [tcl]
      commands = ["unbind dcc n simul *dcc:simul"]

      # Or a multi-line block for procs and binds:
      # code = """
      # proc greet {nick host hand chan} {
      #   putserv "PRIVMSG $chan :Welcome, $nick!"
      # }
      # bind join - * greet
      # """

  For the full reference, see eggdrop.toml (all 128+ settings, fully
  documented) or run 'eggdrop --setup' to generate a personalised copy.

  LEGACY FORMAT: .conf files are still supported. Pass one explicitly:

      eggdrop mybot.conf

  The bot auto-detects the format by file extension (.toml vs. anything
  else). The default config file name is now eggdrop.toml.

PYTHON SCRIPTING

  This fork provides full Python scripting support as a modern
  alternative (or replacement) for Tcl.  Scripts can use the built-in
  eggdrop module and the helper library scripts/eggtools.py.

  BUILDING WITHOUT TCL:

      meson setup builddir/ -Dtcl=disabled
      ninja -C builddir/

  LIST SCRIPTS IN YOUR TOML CONFIG:

      [scripts]
      load = ["scripts/myscript.py"]

  MINIMAL EXAMPLE:

      import eggtools

      @eggtools.on_pub("!hello", "*")
      def greet(nick, host, handle, channel, text):
          eggtools.privmsg(channel, f"Hello, {nick}!")

  EGGTOOLS.PY HIGHLIGHTS:

      · Decorator-based bind registration: @on_pub, @on_msg, @on_join,
        @on_part, @on_kick, @on_mode, @on_nick, @on_sign, @on_notc,
        @on_ctcp, @on_raw, @on_time, @on_cron, @on_dcc, @on_evnt
      · IRC output: privmsg, notice, action, kick, mode, topic, join,
        part, ctcp, ctcp_reply, putserv, putquick, putnow, putdcc,
        puthelp, tagmsg
      · Channel queries: channels, isonchan, getchanhost, chanlist,
        isop, ishalfop, isvoice, isaway, botisop, botishalfop,
        botisvoice, getaccount, nick2hand, hand2nick
      · User database: countusers, validuser, findhandle, userlist
      · Utilities: rand, unixtime, duration, maskhost, hostmatch,
        testip, randstring, ordnumber
      · Timer helper: every(interval_seconds, fn) — cron-bind wrapper
      · IRCv3: cap_req, tagmsg
      · IRCX/Ophion: ircxprop, ircxaccess, ircxcreate, ircxnegotiate
      · alltools.tcl aliases: putmsg, putchan, putnotc, putact,
        strlwr, strupr, strlen, strcmp, stricmp

  MEMBER DATACLASS:

      members = eggtools.chanlist("#mychan")
      for m in members:
          print(m.nick, m.host, m.account)

  See scripts/eggtools.py for the full API with docstrings.

QUICK STARTUP

  Please see the INSTALL file after you finish reading this file.

UPGRADING

  The upgrade process for Eggdrop is very simple, simply download the
  new source code and repeat the compile process. You will want to read
  the NEWS for any new configuration file settings you want to add.
  Please see the UPGRADING file for full details.

  MIGRATION TO TOML: Existing .conf files continue to work with no
  changes. When you are ready to switch, run:

      eggdrop --setup mybot.toml

  and answer the prompts, or manually copy your settings from your
  existing .conf into a .toml file using the new format.

COMMAND LINE

  Eggdrop has some command line options - not many, because most things
  should be defined through the config file. However, sometimes you may
  want to start up the bot in a different mode and the command line
  options let you do that. Basically, the command line for Eggdrop is:

      ./eggdrop [options] [config-file]

  The options available are:

    -s [outfile]: Run the interactive setup wizard. Prompts for key
        settings and writes a ready-to-use TOML config file. If
        outfile is omitted, writes to eggdrop.toml. No chmod needed.
        Example: eggdrop --setup mybot.toml

    -t: Don't background, use terminal. Your console will drop into an
        interactive partyline session, similar to a DCC chat with the
        bot. This is useful for troubleshooting connection issues with
        the bot.

    -c: Don't background, show channel info. Every 10 seconds your screen
        will clear and you will see the current channel status, sort of
        like "top".

    -m: Create userfile. If you don't have a userfile, this will make
        Eggdrop create one and give owner status to the first person
        that introduces himself or herself to it.
        Note: when using the TOML config format with owner = "Nick" set,
        the bot creates the userfile automatically on first run and -m
        is not required.  For legacy .conf files, -m is still needed.

    -h: Show help, then quit.

    -v: Show version info, then quit.

  When using the TOML format, most people only ever use -t (to test
  the bot interactively) and -s (to run the setup wizard).  The -m
  flag is only needed for legacy .conf file setups.

AUTO-STARTING EGGDROP

Systems go down from time to time, taking your Eggdrop along with it.
You may not be not around to restart it manually, so you can instead use
features of the operating system to automatically restart Eggdrop should
it quit for any reason. Eggdrop comes with an autobotchk shell script
that can create either a systemd or crontab entry. The systemd option
will monitor your Eggdrop and a) start it when the machine boots and b)
restart the Eggdrop if it crashes for any reason. The (older) crontab
option will check (by default) every 10 minutes to see if your Eggdrop
is still running, and attempt to restart it if it is not.

  To auto-generate a systemd job, from the Eggdrop install directory,
  simply run:

      ./scripts/autobotchk <eggdrop.toml> -systemd

  To auto-generate a script to check Eggdrop's status and run it via a
  crontab entry, simply run:

      ./scripts/autobotchk <eggdrop.toml>

  This will crontab your bot using the default setup. If you want a list
  of autobotchk options, type './autobotchk'. A crontab example with
  options would be:

      ./scripts/autobotchk <eggdrop.toml> -noemail -5

  This would setup crontab to run the botchk every 5 minutes and not
  send you an email saying that it restarted your bot.

